    "text": "Is your kitchen feeling dated, but a full remodel isn''t in the cards? Cabinet refinishing and repair offer a stunning, cost-effective solution to transform your space without the hefty price tag or extensive disruption of new installations. At ProBuddy, we connect you with skilled professionals who can breathe new life into your existing cabinetry, enhancing both aesthetics and functionality.\n\n**Why Choose Refinishing & Repair?**\nBeyond saving money, refinishing allows you to update your kitchen''s style, repair wear and tear, and even change the entire look with a fresh color or stain. It''s an eco-friendly option that repurposes existing materials, giving your home a significant refresh.\n\n**What to Expect When Hiring a Professional:**\n1.  **Initial Consultation & Assessment:** A ProBuddy expert will visit your home to evaluate your cabinets'' condition, discuss your vision (color, finish, repair needs), and provide a detailed estimate.\n2.  **Preparation is Key:** Professionals will meticulously prepare your kitchen. This involves carefully removing doors and drawers, protecting countertops, floors, and appliances, and setting up a dust-controlled workspace.\n3.  **Repair & Surface Treatment:** Any damage, such as dings, scratches, loose hinges, or structural issues, will be expertly repaired. Surfaces are then thoroughly cleaned, degreased, sanded, and primed to ensure optimal adhesion for the new finish.\n4.  **The New Finish:** Multiple coats of high-quality paint, stain, or lacquer are applied using professional spraying techniques for a smooth, durable, factory-like finish. This often happens off-site in a controlled environment.\n5.  **Reassembly & Finishing Touches:** Once cured, cabinets are carefully reinstalled, hardware is attached, and any final adjustments are made. The result is a beautifully updated kitchen that looks brand new.\n6.  **Timeline:** Depending on the size of your kitchen and the scope of work, the process typically takes 3-10 days, with the most disruptive work often completed off-site.\n\n**Practical Advice for Homeowners:**\n*   **Clear Out Your Cabinets:** Before the project begins, empty all contents from your cabinets and drawers.\n*   **Protect Your Belongings:** While professionals will take precautions, it''s wise to cover nearby furniture or remove delicate items.\n*   **Discuss Hardware:** Decide if you want to reuse existing hardware or install new handles/knobs for an updated look.\n*   **Ask About Materials:** Inquire about the types of paints, stains, and sealants used to ensure durability and a finish that meets your expectations.\n*   **Get Detailed Quotes:** Always compare bids from multiple ProBuddy professionals, ensuring each quote clearly outlines the scope of work, materials, and timeline.\n*   **Check References & Portfolios:** Review past projects and read testimonials to ensure you''re comfortable with the chosen professional''s experience and quality of work.\n\nChoosing professional cabinet refinishing and repair means investing in a high-quality, long-lasting transformation for your kitchen. Let ProBuddy connect you with the right experts to make your vision a reality!"
  }
}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:48:42.178Z' WHERE id = 'KaW5fCcc_e9szSGKpP3K7';
UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{
  "faq": {
    "title": "Frequently Asked Questions About Cabinet Refinishing & Repair",
    "items": [
      {
        "question": "What''s the difference between cabinet refinishing, refacing, and replacing?",
        "answer": "Understanding your options is key:\n\n*   **Refinishing:** This involves restoring your existing cabinet boxes and doors by thoroughly cleaning, sanding, repairing minor imperfections, and then applying a new stain, paint, or clear coat. It keeps your current cabinet structure and style but updates the look. It''s the most budget-friendly and least disruptive option for a fresh aesthetic.\n*   **Refacing:** This option keeps your existing cabinet boxes but replaces the doors, drawer fronts, and applies new veneer to the visible exterior of the cabinet boxes. This allows for a complete change in door style, material, and color without a full tear-out, offering a mid-range cost and disruption level.\n*   **Replacing:** This involves removing all old cabinets and installing entirely new ones. This is the most expensive and disruptive option but provides the greatest flexibility in layout, style, and functionality, allowing for changes in kitchen layout or cabinet configuration."
      },
      {
        "question": "How long does cabinet refinishing typically take?",
        "answer": "The duration of cabinet refinishing depends on the size of your kitchen, the number of cabinets, the complexity of the desired finish, and the condition of the existing cabinets. Generally, the process can take anywhere from **3 to 7 business days** for an average-sized kitchen. This includes meticulous preparation, sanding, cleaning, priming, applying multiple coats of paint or stain, and allowing for proper drying times between coats. Larger kitchens or custom finishes may require additional time."
      },
      {
        "question": "How much does cabinet refinishing cost?",
        "answer": "The cost of cabinet refinishing varies significantly based on several factors: the total number of cabinet doors and drawer fronts, the condition of the existing cabinets (more repairs mean higher cost), the type of finish desired (e.g., solid color paint, glaze, custom stain), and geographical location. While a precise quote requires an on-site assessment, homeowners can typically expect to pay **between $2,000 and $7,000** for a professional refinishing job on an average-sized kitchen. This is generally a fraction of the cost of refacing or replacing cabinets."
      },
      {
        "question": "Will my kitchen be usable during the refinishing process?",
        "answer": "While we strive to minimize disruption, your kitchen will be partially or mostly unusable for certain periods during the refinishing process. We typically remove all cabinet doors and drawer fronts to be worked on off-site in our specialized workshop, which significantly reduces dust and fumes in your home. However, the cabinet frames (boxes) will be prepped and finished on-site. During the on-site work (usually 1-3 days), we highly recommend clearing countertops, removing food items, and avoiding heavy kitchen use due to potential dust, fumes, and wet surfaces. We use professional ventilation and masking to protect your home and keep disruption to a minimum."
      },
      {
        "question": "What types of cabinets can be refinished?",
        "answer": "Most solid wood, wood veneer, and MDF (medium-density fiberboard) cabinets are excellent candidates for refinishing. The key is that the cabinet structure itself is sound, without significant water damage, warping, or delamination. Laminate or thermofoil cabinets can sometimes be refinished, but the process is more complex and may not yield the same durable results as wood-based cabinets. We always recommend a professional assessment to determine if your specific cabinets are suitable for refinishing and to discuss the best approach."
      },
      {
        "question": "How durable is a refinished cabinet finish?",
        "answer": "When performed by experienced professionals using high-quality, professional-grade primers, paints, stains, and clear coats, a refinished cabinet surface is extremely durable and designed to withstand daily kitchen use. We use finishes that are specifically formulated for cabinets, offering excellent resistance to chips, scratches, moisture, and fading. With proper care and cleaning, a professional refinish can last for many years, often comparable to or exceeding the durability of factory finishes on new cabinets."
      },
      {
        "question": "How should I prepare my kitchen for cabinet refinishing?",
        "answer": "To ensure a smooth and efficient refinishing process, we recommend the following preparations:\n\n1.  **Empty Cabinets:** Remove all items from inside your cabinets and drawers.\n2.  **Clear Countertops:** Remove all appliances, decorations, and other items from your countertops.\n3.  **Clean Surfaces:** Give your cabinet exteriors a basic wipe-down to remove obvious grease and food residue.\n4.  **Remove Fragile Items:** Take down any wall hangings, curtains, or other delicate items near the cabinets.\n5.  **Provide Access:** Ensure clear access to all cabinets and the surrounding work area.\n\nWe will handle the extensive deep cleaning, degreasing, masking, and dust protection required for the refinishing process itself."
      }
    ]
  }
}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:48:45.995Z' WHERE id = 'R9wx_TvK-Q_6ZbpL-uYop';
