UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{"content": {
  "title": "Restore, Reimagine, Rejuvenate: Professional Furniture Refinishing",
  "text": "Is that cherished antique dresser looking a little tired? Or perhaps your family dining table has seen one too many spills? Don''t toss it – transform it! Professional furniture refinishing breathes new life into your beloved pieces, restoring their original glory or reimagining them with a fresh, modern look. It''s an eco-friendly, cost-effective way to preserve history, personalize your space, and prevent perfectly good furniture from ending up in a landfill.\n\n**Why Choose a Professional?**\nWhile DIY refinishing can be tempting, achieving a truly flawless, durable finish requires specialized skills, tools, and expertise. Professionals understand different wood types, finishes, and the intricate steps involved in proper stripping, sanding, staining, and sealing. They can tackle complex repairs, ensure an even application, and deliver a finish that not only looks stunning but also stands the test of time, saving you hours of frustration and potential costly mistakes.\n\n**What to Expect During the Process:**\n1.  **Consultation & Assessment**: Your refinisher will examine your furniture, discuss your vision (color, sheen, desired look), and provide a detailed quote and timeline.\n2.  **Preparation is Key**: The piece will be thoroughly cleaned, and old finishes will be meticulously stripped away. This often involves careful sanding to create a smooth, pristine surface ready for new life.\n3.  **Repairs & Restoration**: Dents, scratches, loose joints, or minor damage will be expertly repaired, ensuring structural integrity and a flawless appearance.\n4.  **Staining or Painting**: This is where your vision comes to life! Whether you opt for a rich stain to highlight natural wood grain or a vibrant paint color, the professional will apply it evenly and skillfully.\n5.  **Finishing & Protection**: Multiple coats of a protective topcoat (lacquer, varnish, polyurethane, oil finish) will be applied. This step is crucial for durability, protecting against spills, scratches, and daily wear.\n6.  **Curing Time**: Patience is a virtue! The final finish needs time to fully cure and harden. Your refinisher will advise on the appropriate waiting period before heavy use.\n\n**Practical Advice for Homeowners:**\n*   **Define Your Vision**: Gather inspiration photos and be clear about the color, finish (matte, satin, gloss), and overall style you desire.\n*   **Consider the Piece''s Value**: Is it a family heirloom, a valuable antique, or a sentimental piece? This can influence the level of restoration or type of finish you choose.\n*   **Get Multiple Quotes**: Compare estimates, but don''t just go for the cheapest option. Look for experience, portfolio examples, and clear communication.\n*   **Ask for Portfolios & References**: See their previous work and hear from other satisfied clients.\n*   **Understand the Timeline**: Professional refinishing is a detailed process that takes time. Discuss expected turnaround times upfront.\n*   **Prepare Your Item**: Remove any hardware (knobs, pulls) and give the piece a basic wipe-down before the professional picks it up or you drop it off.\n*   **Discuss Logistics**: Clarify pickup, delivery, and storage arrangements.\n\nInvest in professional furniture refinishing, and watch your cherished pieces transform into stunning focal points that reflect your style and stand the test of time. Ready to revive your furniture? Find a trusted refinishing expert on ProBuddy today!"
}}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:49:22.117Z' WHERE id = 'N5eNCFaGwqydMaxUbGKuo';
UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{"faq": {
  "title": "Frequently Asked Questions About Furniture Refinishing",
  "items": [
    {
      "question": "What types of furniture can be refinished, and are there any limitations?",
      "answer": "Most solid wood furniture can be refinished, including tables, chairs, dressers, cabinets, and antique pieces. The primary limitation is the material; pressed wood, particleboard, or veneer that is too thin or extensively damaged may not be suitable for traditional refinishing, as these materials can''t withstand sanding or stripping processes effectively. We always assess the piece to determine its suitability and discuss the best approach with you."
    },
    {
      "question": "What''s the typical process for furniture refinishing?",
      "answer": "The process generally involves several key steps: 1. **Inspection & Assessment:** Evaluating the furniture''s condition, wood type, and existing finish. 2. **Disassembly (if needed):** Taking apart components like drawers or hardware. 3. **Stripping:** Removing the old finish using chemical strippers or careful sanding. 4. **Repair:** Addressing any structural damage, loose joints, or veneer issues. 5. **Sanding:** Preparing the wood surface with progressively finer grits to achieve smoothness. 6. **Staining (optional):** Applying a stain to achieve the desired color. 7. **Finishing:** Applying multiple coats of a protective topcoat (e.g., lacquer, varnish, polyurethane, oil finish), with light sanding between coats for durability and smoothness. 8. **Curing & Reassembly:** Allowing the finish to cure properly before reassembling hardware and returning the piece."
    },
    {
      "question": "How long does furniture refinishing usually take?",
      "answer": "The timeframe can vary significantly based on the size, complexity, condition of the furniture, and the type of finish applied. A small chair might take 1-2 weeks, while a large dining table or an intricate antique dresser could take 3-6 weeks or even longer. This includes time for stripping, repairs, multiple coats of finish, and crucial curing time for the finish to harden properly. We''ll provide an estimated timeline with your quote."
    },
    {
      "question": "How much does furniture refinishing cost, and what factors influence the price?",
      "answer": "Refinishing costs vary widely. Key factors include: **Size and Complexity:** Larger or more intricate pieces with carvings, multiple drawers, or delicate components require more labor. **Current Condition:** Extensive damage, loose joints, missing veneer, or multiple layers of old paint will increase repair time and cost. **Type of Wood & Finish:** Some woods are harder to work with, and certain high-durability or specialized finishes can be more expensive. **Desired Outcome:** A complete stripping and refinishing will cost more than a simple touch-up or re-coating. **Logistics:** Pickup and delivery services may also factor into the overall price. We provide a detailed, no-obligation quote after assessing your specific piece."
    },
    {
      "question": "Can you match an existing finish or color, or achieve a specific look?",
      "answer": "Yes, matching an existing finish or achieving a specific color is a common request and one of our specialties. We can blend custom stains and finishes to closely match other furniture pieces in your home or to achieve a particular aesthetic you''re aiming for. Providing a sample or a clear photo of the desired color/finish is helpful. We often create samples for your approval before applying it to the entire piece."
    },
    {
      "question": "What kind of finishes do you use, and which is best for my furniture?",
      "answer": "We use a variety of high-quality professional finishes, including lacquers, varnishes, polyurethanes, and oil finishes. The ''best'' finish depends on the furniture''s intended use, desired look, and durability requirements. **Lacquers:** Fast-drying, durable, and offer a smooth, clear finish. **Varnishes/Polyurethanes:** Extremely durable and water-resistant, ideal for high-traffic items. **Oil Finishes:** Penetrate the wood for a natural, hand-rubbed look and feel, easy to repair, often used on antiques. We will discuss the pros and cons of each option with you to recommend the most suitable finish for your specific piece and needs."
    },
