UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{"content": {
  "title": "Never Lose Power Again: Professional Generator Installation for Your Home",
  "text": "Imagine a world where power outages are just a minor inconvenience, not a major disruption. With a professionally installed home generator, that world is within reach. At ProBuddy, we connect you with certified experts who ensure your home stays powered, no matter what Mother Nature throws your way.\n\n**Why Professional Installation Matters**\nInstalling a whole-home standby generator is a complex task that involves electrical, plumbing (for fuel lines), and construction work. It''s not a DIY project. Professional installation guarantees:\n*   **Safety**: Correct wiring and fuel line connections prevent hazards.\n*   **Code Compliance**: Adherence to local building codes and regulations, often requiring permits.\n*   **Optimal Performance**: Proper sizing and placement ensure your generator runs efficiently when needed most.\n*   **Warranty Protection**: Many manufacturers require professional installation for warranty validity.\n\n**What to Expect from Your Generator Installation Journey**\nWhen you choose a ProBuddy professional for your generator installation, here''s a typical roadmap:\n1.  **Initial Consultation & Site Assessment**: An expert will visit your home to assess your power needs, recommend the right size and type of generator (e.g., natural gas, propane), and determine the best location for the unit, considering noise, ventilation, and fuel access.\n2.  **Permitting & Planning**: Your contractor will handle all necessary permits with local authorities, ensuring the installation meets all municipal and electrical codes.\n3.  **Site Preparation**: This involves preparing a stable concrete pad for the generator, running necessary electrical conduits, and installing fuel lines to connect to your home''s natural gas supply or a propane tank.\n4.  **Installation & Connections**: The generator unit is set in place, and expert technicians will connect it to your home''s electrical system via an automatic transfer switch (ATS). The ATS senses power outages and seamlessly switches your home''s power to the generator, then back to utility power when it''s restored.\n5.  **Testing & Commissioning**: Once installed, the generator undergoes rigorous testing to ensure all systems are functioning correctly, from startup to power transfer.\n6.  **Homeowner Orientation**: Your technician will walk you through the basic operation, maintenance schedule, and answer any questions you may have, ensuring you''re comfortable with your new power solution.\n\n**Practical Advice for Homeowners**\n*   **Get Multiple Quotes**: Compare proposals from several licensed and insured contractors.\n*   **Ask About Warranties**: Understand what''s covered for both the generator unit and the installation labor.\n*   **Consider Maintenance Plans**: Regular maintenance is crucial for generator longevity and reliability. Inquire about annual service agreements.\n*   **Don''t Skimp on Sizing**: An undersized generator won''t power all your essentials. Be honest about your needs during the assessment.\n\nEmpower your home with reliable backup power. A professional generator installation from a ProBuddy expert offers peace of mind, knowing your family and property are protected during any outage. Get started today by requesting a free consultation!"
}}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:50:00.919Z' WHERE id = 'qCJLE5f4EUw5SEMMMkkTl';
UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{
  "faq": {
    "title": "Frequently Asked Questions About Generator Installation",
    "items": [
      {
        "question": "What are the main types of home generators, and which one is right for me?",
        "answer": "There are primarily two types: portable and standby (or whole-house) generators. Portable generators are manually operated, require refueling, and typically power a few essential appliances via extension cords or a manual transfer switch. Standby generators are permanently installed, connect directly to your home''s electrical system and fuel source (natural gas or propane), and automatically turn on when utility power is lost. For seamless, automatic power during an outage, a standby generator is usually the preferred choice for homeowners, offering convenience and the ability to power most, if not all, of your home."
      },
      {
        "question": "How do I determine the right size generator for my home?",
        "answer": "Determining the correct generator size involves calculating your home''s power needs. This means identifying all the appliances and systems you want to power during an outage (e.g., HVAC, refrigerator, well pump, lights, computers). Professionals perform a load calculation, considering both the running wattage and the higher starting (surge) wattage of certain appliances. It''s crucial not to undersize the generator, which can lead to overloading, or oversize it unnecessarily. A professional assessment by an electrician or generator specialist is highly recommended to ensure you get the most efficient and appropriate size for your specific needs."
      },
      {
        "question": "What does the generator installation process typically involve?",
        "answer": "The installation process typically begins with a site assessment and load calculation. Once the generator size and type are determined, the steps generally include: securing necessary permits, preparing a concrete pad for the generator, running electrical conduit and wiring from the generator to an automatic transfer switch (ATS) connected to your home''s main electrical panel, connecting the generator to its fuel source (natural gas line or propane tank), and finally, testing the system. The installer will also typically provide a homeowner orientation on how the system works and what to expect."
      },
      {
        "question": "What permits and inspections are required for generator installation?",
        "answer": "Generator installation requires several permits and inspections to ensure safety and compliance with local building codes. You will typically need an electrical permit, and if you''re connecting to a natural gas line, a plumbing or gas permit may also be required. These permits ensure that the installation meets all safety standards and local regulations. A licensed professional will handle the permit application process and schedule the necessary inspections (e.g., electrical, gas, final inspection) with the local authorities upon completion of the work."
