UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{
  "faq": {
    "title": "Frequently Asked Questions About Carpet Installation",
    "items": [
      {
        "question": "What is the typical carpet installation process from start to finish?",
        "answer": "The process usually begins with a consultation and precise measurement of your rooms. Next, if applicable, your old carpet and padding will be removed and disposed of. The subfloor is then inspected and prepared to ensure it''s clean, dry, and level. The new padding is laid, followed by the new carpet, which is stretched, cut to fit, and secured along the edges. Finally, the installer will clean up any debris, vacuum the new carpet, and conduct a final walkthrough with you to ensure your satisfaction."
      },
      {
        "question": "How long does carpet installation usually take?",
        "answer": "The duration of carpet installation varies depending on the size and complexity of the job. A single average-sized room might take a few hours, while an entire house can take anywhere from one to three days. Factors like furniture moving, extensive subfloor repairs, the presence of stairs, and intricate room layouts can extend the timeline. Your installer should provide an estimated completion time after the initial assessment."
      },
      {
        "question": "What factors determine the overall cost of carpet installation?",
        "answer": "The total cost is influenced by several factors: the type and quality of carpet and padding you choose (materials are a major component), the total square footage of the area to be carpeted, labor rates for installation, costs for removing and disposing of old carpet, any necessary subfloor repairs (e.g., patching, leveling), and additional services like moving furniture, installing on stairs, or working with complex room shapes. Always get a detailed, itemized quote."
      },
      {
        "question": "Do I need to move my furniture and remove the old carpet myself before the installers arrive?",
        "answer": "While many professional installers offer furniture moving and old carpet removal as part of their service, it often comes with an additional fee. You can choose to save on costs by moving smaller items and personal belongings yourself. For larger, heavier furniture, most homeowners opt for the installer''s service. Discuss these details with your installer beforehand to clarify what''s included and what you might need to do."
      },
      {
        "question": "What kind of subfloor preparation is usually needed before installing new carpet?",
        "answer": "Proper subfloor preparation is crucial for a smooth, long-lasting carpet installation. This involves inspecting the subfloor for any damage such as cracks, loose boards, moisture, or unevenness. Any necessary repairs, like patching holes, leveling uneven areas, or securing loose sections, must be completed. The subfloor is then thoroughly cleaned of dust, debris, and old adhesive to ensure a clean, stable surface for the new padding and carpet."
      },
      {
        "question": "What''s the best way to choose the right carpet for my home?",
        "answer": "Choosing the right carpet involves considering several factors: the room''s traffic level (high-traffic areas need durable fibers like nylon), the room''s purpose (soft, plush for bedrooms; stain-resistant for family rooms), your budget, and your aesthetic preferences. Research different carpet fibers (nylon, polyester, wool, olefin), styles (cut pile, loop pile, frieze), and colors. It''s highly recommended to obtain samples and see them in your home''s lighting before making a final decision."
      },
      {
        "question": "What kind of warranty or guarantee should I expect for carpet installation?",
        "answer": "Reputable carpet installers typically offer a labor warranty, which covers any issues arising from the installation itself, such as seams coming apart or improper stretching. This warranty usually ranges from 1 to 5 years. Separately, the carpet manufacturer provides its own warranty, which covers the carpet''s quality, wear, and stain resistance. Always ask your installer to clarify both the labor warranty and how to register for the manufacturer''s warranty."
