UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{"faq": {
  "title": "Frequently Asked Questions About Epoxy Floor Coating",
  "items": [
    {
      "question": "What exactly is epoxy flooring, and what are its main benefits for homeowners?",
      "answer": "Epoxy flooring is a durable, multi-layer coating system applied over concrete floors. It''s made from a thermosetting resin that, when mixed with a hardener, creates a rigid plastic material that''s strong and resistant to degradation. For homeowners, the main benefits include exceptional durability against abrasions, impacts, and chemicals; enhanced aesthetics with a wide range of colors and finishes; easy maintenance due to its seamless, non-porous surface; and improved safety through slip-resistant additives. It''s ideal for garages, basements, workshops, and even interior living spaces."
    },
    {
      "question": "How long does an epoxy floor coating typically last, and what factors influence its lifespan?",
      "answer": "With professional installation and proper maintenance, an epoxy floor coating can last anywhere from 10 to 20 years, sometimes even longer. Several factors influence its lifespan, including the quality of the epoxy materials used, the thoroughness of the surface preparation (which is crucial), the amount of foot and vehicle traffic it endures, exposure to UV light (which can cause yellowing or chalking over time if not UV-stable), and whether it''s regularly cleaned and maintained according to recommendations. High-quality, professional-grade epoxy systems generally offer superior longevity."
    },
    {
      "question": "What does the epoxy floor installation process involve, and how long does it usually take?",
      "answer": "The installation process is multi-faceted and typically takes 2 to 5 days, followed by a curing period. It begins with critical surface preparation, including cleaning, degreasing, repairing cracks or spalls, and often diamond grinding or shot blasting the concrete to create a profile for optimal adhesion. Next, a primer coat is applied, followed by one or more layers of colored epoxy. Decorative flakes or aggregates may be broadcast at this stage. Finally, a clear topcoat is applied for added protection and finish. Light foot traffic is usually permissible after 24-72 hours, but it''s crucial to wait 5-7 days before allowing vehicle traffic or heavy objects to ensure full cure and maximize durability."
    },
    {
      "question": "Is epoxy flooring a suitable DIY project, or is professional installation recommended?",
      "answer": "While DIY epoxy kits are available, professional installation is strongly recommended for optimal results and longevity. The success of an epoxy floor hinges on meticulous surface preparation, precise mixing ratios, and proper application techniques, which are difficult for an amateur to achieve. Mistakes in preparation can lead to peeling, bubbling, or premature failure. Professionals have specialized equipment for concrete grinding, access to higher-quality commercial-grade epoxy products, and the expertise to handle unexpected issues, ensuring a durable, aesthetically pleasing, and long-lasting finish backed by a warranty."
    },
    {
      "question": "How do I clean and maintain my epoxy floor to keep it looking new?",
      "answer": "Epoxy floors are remarkably easy to maintain. For general cleaning, a soft-bristle broom, dust mop, or commercial floor scrubber is recommended for dry debris. For spills or dirt, use a soft mop with warm water and a mild, pH-neutral cleaner. Avoid abrasive cleaners, harsh chemicals (like citrus-based cleaners or vinegar), and steel wool, as these can dull the finish or leave residues. Promptly clean up any spills, especially oil, grease, or chemicals, to prevent staining. Placing mats in high-traffic areas or under vehicles can further protect the coating from excessive wear and tear."
    },
    {
      "question": "Is epoxy flooring slippery, especially when wet?",
      "answer": "A plain, smooth epoxy finish can be slippery when wet, similar to polished concrete or tile. However, professional installers can incorporate anti-slip additives into the topcoat to significantly increase traction and enhance safety. These additives, such as fine aluminum oxide or silica sand, create a slightly textured surface without compromising the ease of cleaning. If slip resistance is a concern for your application (e.g., a garage where water might be tracked in), always discuss this option with your ProBuddy professional."
    },
    {
      "question": "Can epoxy flooring be applied over existing concrete, even if it has cracks or damage?",
      "answer": "Yes, epoxy flooring can be applied over existing concrete, but the condition of the concrete is paramount. Any cracks, spalls, or unevenness must be thoroughly repaired and prepared *before* the epoxy application. Epoxy will not bridge gaps or fix structural issues; in fact, it tends to highlight imperfections if the surface isn''t properly prepped. Professionals will grind, patch, and fill all necessary areas to create a smooth, sound, and properly profiled substrate, ensuring maximum adhesion and a flawless finish for your new epoxy floor."
    }
  ]
}}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:51:11.788Z' WHERE id = '_XyjLU2YnNZcittpN8v-I';
