UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{
  "content": {
    "title": "Revitalize Your Home: Professional Hardwood Floor Refinishing",
    "text": "Is your once-beautiful hardwood floor looking dull, scratched, or simply showing its age? Hardwood floor refinishing isn''t just a cosmetic upgrade; it''s an investment that restores the beauty, durability, and value of your home. At ProBuddy, we connect you with skilled professionals ready to transform your floors from worn to wonderful.\n\n**What is Hardwood Floor Refinishing?**\nRefinishing involves sanding down the existing finish and a thin layer of the wood to remove imperfections, scratches, and old stains. Once the bare wood is exposed and smooth, new stain (if desired) and several coats of protective finish are applied, bringing your floors back to life with a fresh, resilient surface.\n\n**Benefits of Professional Refinishing:**\n*   **Restored Beauty:** Eliminate years of wear and tear, revealing the natural warmth and grain of your wood.\n*   **Enhanced Durability:** New protective coats shield your floors from future scratches, spills, and daily wear.\n*   **Increased Home Value:** Beautiful, well-maintained hardwood floors are a significant selling point and boost curb appeal.\n*   **Extended Lifespan:** Proper refinishing can add decades to the life of your hardwood floors, delaying the need for costly replacement.\n*   **Improved Hygiene:** A smooth, sealed surface is easier to clean and less likely to harbor allergens.\n\n**When to Consider Refinishing:**\nLook for signs like deep scratches, scuffs that go beyond the finish, dullness, discoloration, or areas where the finish has completely worn through. If your floors look tired and detract from your home''s aesthetic, it''s likely time for a professional touch.\n\n**What to Expect During the Process:**\n1.  **Consultation & Quote:** A ProBuddy professional will assess your floors, discuss your vision (stain color, finish type like matte, semi-gloss, or high-gloss), and provide a detailed estimate.\n2.  **Preparation:** You''ll need to clear the room of all furniture, rugs, and décor. Our pros will protect adjacent areas, walls, and built-ins.\n3.  **Sanding:** Using specialized equipment with advanced dust containment systems, multiple passes are made with progressively finer grits of sandpaper to strip the old finish and smooth the wood.\n4.  **Staining (Optional):** If you choose to change or deepen your floor''s color, stain is applied evenly and allowed to dry.\n5.  **Finishing Coats:** Several layers of durable polyurethane (or other chosen finish) are applied, with drying time between coats. This provides the protective layer and desired sheen.\n6.  **Curing Time:** While floors are often walkable within a day, it''s crucial to allow several days for the finish to fully cure before placing heavy furniture or rugs back, and a few weeks for full hardness. Your professional will provide specific guidelines.\n\n**Practical Advice for Homeowners:**\n*   **Plan Ahead:** Schedule your refinishing when you can be away from the main living areas or even out of the house for a few days, especially if you''re sensitive to odors.\n*   **Dust Management:** While professionals use dust containment, expect some residual fine dust throughout your home. Plan for a thorough cleaning afterward.\n*   **Odor & Ventilation:** Modern finishes have less odor, but proper ventilation is still essential.\n*   **Post-Refinishing Care:** Follow your professional''s advice on cleaning and maintenance to keep your newly refinished floors looking their best for years to come.\n\nChoose ProBuddy for a hassle-free experience and connect with top-rated hardwood refinishing experts who deliver stunning results. Get ready to fall in love with your floors all over again!"
  }
}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:51:32.021Z' WHERE id = 'jV357nT0OP2ifaOLKY0dS';
UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{"faq": {
  "title": "Frequently Asked Questions About Hardwood Floor Refinishing",
  "items": [
    {
      "question": "How much does hardwood floor refinishing cost?",
      "answer": "The cost of hardwood floor refinishing can vary significantly based on several factors, including the total square footage, the current condition of your floors, the type of wood, the desired stain and finish, and local labor rates. Generally, homeowners can expect to pay between $3 to $8 per square foot. For example, refinishing a 1,000 sq ft area might range from $3,000 to $8,000. This price typically includes all stages of the process: sanding, minor repairs, staining (if chosen), and applying multiple coats of protective finish."
    },
    {
      "question": "How long does the refinishing process take, and when can I walk on my floors again?",
      "answer": "The duration of the refinishing process depends on the size of the area and the specific finishes used. For an average-sized home (500-1000 sq ft), the entire process, including sanding, staining, and applying multiple coats of finish with adequate drying time between coats, typically takes 3 to 7 days. You can usually walk lightly on the floors in socks after 24-48 hours following the final coat. However, it''s crucial to wait 3-7 days before moving furniture back and at least 2 weeks (and ideally 30 days) for the finish to fully cure and achieve maximum hardness before placing rugs or heavy items."
    },
    {
      "question": "Is hardwood floor refinishing a very dusty process?",
      "answer": "Modern hardwood floor refinishing has significantly reduced dust compared to older methods. Most professional companies, including ProBuddy, use advanced dustless or low-dust sanding systems. These systems connect powerful vacuums directly to the sanding equipment, capturing 90-95% of airborne dust particles. While it''s nearly impossible to achieve 100% dust-free results, these technologies make the process much cleaner and less disruptive for homeowners. We still recommend covering sensitive items and expect a light cleanup afterward."
    },
    {
      "question": "Can all hardwood floors be refinished?",
      "answer": "Most solid hardwood floors can be refinished multiple times due to their thick wear layer. Engineered hardwood floors can also be refinished, but the number of times depends on the thickness of their real wood veneer layer. Floors with very thin veneers (typically less than 2mm) or floors that have been refinished too many times and are sanded down to the tongue and groove may not be candidates for refinishing and might require replacement. A professional assessment is the best way to determine if your floors are suitable for refinishing."
    },
    {
      "question": "What''s the difference between refinishing and recoating (or screening and recoating)?",
      "answer": "Refinishing involves sanding down to the bare wood, removing all old stain and finish, and then applying new stain (optional) and multiple coats of protective finish. This is necessary for floors with deep scratches, significant wear spots, or discoloration. Recoating (also known as screening and recoating) is a less invasive process where the existing finish is lightly abraded (scuffed) to remove minor surface scratches and dullness, and then a new topcoat of finish is applied. Recoating is suitable for floors with minor wear where the finish is still largely intact, providing a refresh without the full sanding process, and is quicker and less expensive than full refinishing."
    },
    {
      "question": "What should I do to prepare my home for hardwood floor refinishing?",
      "answer": "To prepare for refinishing, you''ll need to completely empty the rooms where work will be done, removing all furniture, rugs, and décor. We also recommend removing wall hangings and curtains to protect them from potential dust or accidental damage. If possible, disconnect and remove appliances. Our team will cover doorways and vents to help contain dust, but you might consider shutting off your HVAC system during sanding hours. Plan to be out of the house, or at least out of the immediate work area, during the process due to noise and fumes from the finish."
    },
    {
      "question": "How long will my newly refinished floors last?",
      "answer": "With proper care and maintenance, a professional hardwood floor refinish can last anywhere from 10 to 20 years, or even longer. The lifespan depends on several factors, including the type of finish used (e.g., oil-based vs. water-based polyurethane), the amount of foot traffic, the presence of pets, and how well you maintain them. Regular cleaning using appropriate hardwood floor cleaners, promptly cleaning spills, using furniture pads, and avoiding abrasive materials will significantly extend the life and beauty of your refinished floors."
    }
  ]
}}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:51:31.638Z' WHERE id = 'FkW6KbSqO8v_4w-sXB049';
