UPDATE page_sections SET content = '{
  "title": "Hardwood Floor Refinishing: What Homeowners Should Know",
  "tips": [
    "**Vet Your Professionals Thoroughly:** Obtain at least 3-4 quotes from licensed, insured, and reputable companies. Ask for references, view their portfolio, and inquire about their specific experience with your type of hardwood and desired finish.",
    "**Understand the Refinishing Process & Finish Options:** Discuss sanding methods (e.g., dustless vs. traditional), types of finishes (water-based for faster drying and less odor, oil-based for durability and an ambering effect), and the number of coats. This helps set realistic expectations for timeline and results.",
    "**Prepare Your Home Adequately:** Clear all furniture, rugs, curtains, and wall decor from the areas to be refinished. Consider removing baseboards for a cleaner finish. Arrange for temporary relocation of pets and sensitive family members during the project, especially if strong fumes or significant dust are expected.",
    "**Prioritize Dust Control and Ventilation:** Inquire about the contractor''s dust containment systems (e.g., HEPA vacuums). During the process, ensure adequate ventilation by opening windows (if weather permits) and discuss any necessary HVAC adjustments to minimize dust circulation and odor.",
    "**Respect Drying and Curing Times:** Understand that ''dry-to-touch'' is not ''fully cured.'' Avoid walking on newly finished floors for the recommended period, and wait even longer (often 7-30 days, depending on the finish) before replacing rugs, heavy furniture, or resuming normal heavy traffic to allow the finish to fully harden.",
    "**Set Realistic Expectations for Imperfections:** While refinishing dramatically improves floors, deep pet stains, severe water damage, or very deep gouges may not be entirely removed. Discuss these specific concerns with your contractor beforehand to understand what is realistically achievable.",
    "**Follow Post-Refinishing Care Instructions:** Your contractor should provide specific guidelines for cleaning and maintaining your newly refinished floors. Generally, use only recommended hardwood floor cleaners, avoid excessive moisture, and place felt pads under all furniture legs to prevent scratches."
  ]
}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:51:46.324Z' WHERE id = '5lc9STXhizzP2pFhfXTF2';
