  "title": "Deck or Porch Remodel/Addition: Tips for Homeowners",
  "tips": [
    "**Define Your Vision & Budget Clearly:** Before contacting professionals, have a clear idea of your desired design, materials (e.g., wood vs. composite), and a realistic budget. This helps contractors provide accurate quotes and ensures your expectations are met.",
    "**Research Local Codes & Permits:** Understand your local building codes, zoning regulations, and HOA requirements. A reputable contractor will handle the permitting process, but knowing the rules beforehand can prevent costly delays or rework.",
    "**Obtain Multiple Detailed Bids:** Get at least three comprehensive bids from licensed and insured contractors. Compare not just the total price, but also the scope of work, materials specified, payment schedule, timeline, and warranty information.",
    "**Establish Clear Communication Channels:** Agree on a communication plan with your contractor (e.g., weekly meetings, daily check-ins). Promptly address any questions or concerns to keep the project moving smoothly and avoid misunderstandings.",
    "**Monitor Progress & Quality (Respectfully):** While trusting your professional, conduct regular, agreed-upon site visits to ensure the work is progressing according to the contract and meets quality standards. Raise any concerns immediately.",
    "**Conduct a Thorough Final Walkthrough:** Before making the final payment, perform a detailed inspection with your contractor. Create a ''punch list'' of any unfinished items or necessary corrections and ensure they are resolved to your complete satisfaction.",
    "**Understand Ongoing Maintenance Requirements:** Ask your contractor for specific instructions on how to properly maintain your new deck or porch, including cleaning, sealing, and any recommended annual inspections to maximize its lifespan and appearance."
  ]
}', updated_at = '2026-02-17T19:52:50.462Z' WHERE id = 'AhfanpUjVGPkfkSXoETCN';
